  <generalInformation><![CDATA[<h3>Beginners skiing and snowboarding in Livigno</h3>
<p>Beginners are very well catered for, the nursery slopes at village level encourage first timers to progress to higher runs. There are easy blues from the top to the bottom of the mountain.</p>
<h3>Intermediates skiing and snowboarding in Livigno<strong><br /></strong></h3>
<p>Livigno is an Intermediates paradise, with refreshingly few lift queues. Head up the Carosello gondola for a large selection of wide, sunny pistes then cross the mountain to the stunning Costaccia ski area above the old town. Hop on the ski bus to the Mottolino area with its more testing terrain, confidence building black runs and the peaceful, scenic Trepalle runs.</p>
<h3>Advanced skiing and snowboarding in Livigno<strong><br /></strong></h3>
<p>Freeride adventures will capture the imagination of the advanced skier.</p>
<h3>Off piste and snow parks in Livigno </h3>
<p>Livigno has two extreme snow parks, of which the Mottolino side has been been voted the best in Italy. Whilst known for it's daunting jumps there's a lot fun to be had on the rails, boxes and smaller jumps. Be sure to check what's on in Livigno so as not to miss any freestyle displays. </p>
<p>Livigno and the Alta Valtellina valley offer some superb freeride opportunities. On the Mottlino side however, off piste is only permitted in certain areas and you must be accompanied by a local guide. </p>
<h3>Cross-country skiing in Livigno </h3>
<p>Livigno has over 30 kilometres of cross-country tracks catering to both amateurs and professionals. The tracks start in the Forcola and Alpe Vago areas. Here professionals can train at high altitude whilst amateurs enjoy the plateau's and scenery of the surrounding peaks. There are also opportunities to book a lesson with a cross-country instructor if you've never done it before and you'd like to try it out.</p>]]></generalInformation>
